Daily Air Quality Report for 42 Chinese Cities 
Seven Chinese cities, namely Tianjin, Taiyuan, Shenyang, Nanchang,
Lanzhou, Xining and Urumqi, reported slight air pollution today, with
the highest pollution reading at 190 in Lanzhou.
According to the daily air quality report released by the China
Environmental Monitoring Center, level two, or fairly good air quality,
was recorded in other 28 cities.
These cities are Beijing, Shijiazhuang, Hohhot, Dalian, Changchun,
Harbin, Shanghai, Nanjing, Suzhou, Hangzhou, Wenzhou, Fuzhou, Xiamen,
Jinan, Qingdao, Yantai, Zhengzhou, Wuhan, Changsha, Guangzhou, Shantou,
Zhanjiang, Chongqing, Chengdu, Guiyang, Kunming, Lhasa and Xi'an.
Particulates less than 10 microns in size were the major pollutants in
most of these cities, except Shijiazhuang, Changsha, Chongqing and
Guiyang, where sulfur dioxide was the major air pollutant.
Seven cities -- Nantong, Hefei, Shenzhen, Zhuhai, Nanning, Haikou and
Yingchuan -- reported excellent air quality.
The center classifies air quality in China's urban areas into five
levels: level one or excellent (pollution reading: not exceeding 50),
level two or fairly good (pollution reading: 51 to 100), level three or
slightly polluted (pollution reading: 101 to 200), level four or poor
(pollution reading: 201 to 300), and level five or hazardous (pollution
reading: over 301).
The 42 cities monitored by the center include the four municipalities
of Beijing, Tianjin, Shanghai and Chongqing, provincial capitals and
major cities in the economically developed coastal areas.
